<DocsLayout
  title="Event bus & journal"
  eyebrow="Architecture"
  description="The shared spine that ties the harness, UI, and observers together."
  prev={{ href: "/docs/extensibility/", title: "Extensibility" }}
  next={{ href: "/docs/sessions/", title: "Sessions & resume" }}
>
  <p>
    Every meaningful state transition in <code>godex</code> is an event. Events are the only
    contract between the runner and everything else: the TUI, the ACP transport, the
    app-server, the JSONL journal, OpenTelemetry, and any future RL or replay system.
  </p>

  <h2>Why a bus</h2>
  <p>
    A coding agent has many simultaneous consumers of the same information: a UI rendering
    deltas, a journal persisting them, a transport relaying them to a remote client, and
    potentially an observer collecting trajectories for training. Coupling the runner to
    each of these directly makes the runner brittle. With a typed event bus, adding a new
    consumer is a subscription, not a refactor.
  </p>

  <h2>What flows through it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Turn lifecycle: <code>turn_started</code>, <code>turn_completed</code>, <code>turn_cancelled</code>.</li>
    <li>Assistant message chunks (text deltas).</li>
    <li>Tool call lifecycle: pending, running, completed, failed.</li>
    <li>Permission requests and resolutions.</li>
    <li>Workspace mutations: file edits, todo updates, memory writes.</li>
    <li>Session lifecycle: created, resumed, closed, compacted.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The JSONL journal</h2>
  <p>
    Every event is also written to a per-session JSONL file on disk. This is the source of
    truth for resume: when you reopen a session, the journal is replayed to reconstruct
    state. It is also the source of truth for debugging — you can <code>cat</code> a session
    journal and read exactly what happened, in order.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>One stream, many readers.</strong> If you can subscribe to the bus, you can
    build something on top of gode without modifying it. That is the point.
  </div>

  <h2>OpenTelemetry</h2>
  <p>
    The runner emits OTLP/gRPC spans alongside events. <code>make run</code> exports to
    <code>localhost:4317</code> by default, and <code>./jaeger.sh</code> spins up a local
    Jaeger to look at them.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
